    "Mark Allan Powell, Mark E. Biddle, Martin Luther": "). Yet another isolated tradition reports the\n[v_Deu_3_12] [v_Deu_3_13] [v_Deu_3_14] [v_Deu_3_15] [v_Deu_3_16] [v_Deu_3_17] [v_Deu_3_18] [v_Deu_3_19] [v_Deu_3_20] [v_Deu_3_21] [v_Deu_3_22] Deuteronomy 3:12-22\nindependent campaign of a certain\nNabah (\n40. D. Olson argues that the paranesis is struc-\ntured concentrically with the introduction (vv. 1-4)\nparalleling the conclusion (\nv. 40). An inner frame-\nwork stresses the \u201cunique greatness of Israel\u2019s\nwisdom and God\u2019s nearness\u201d (vv. 5-8 // vv. 32-\n39). The body of the chapter, vv. 9-31, offers\nthree paradigms for keeping the covenant, namely\nthe \u201cHoreb-Creation-Egypt paradigm from the\npast\u201d (vv. 9-20), the \u201cMoses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`-People paradigm of\nthe present\u201d (vv. 21-24), and the \u201cExile-Return\nparadigm of the future\u201d (vv. 25-31).\nD. Knapp, Deuteronomium 4: literarische Analyse und theolo-\ngische Interpretation (G\u00f6ttinger theologischer Arbeiten 35;\nG\u00f6ttingen: Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht, 1987), 27-"
